          <div class="service-box blue">
            <i class="ri-discuss-line icon"></i>
            <h3>Overview</h3>
            <p>Donating blood is a voluntary action that can help save lives. There are several types of blood donation.
              Each type helps meet different medical needs Whole blood donation is the most common type of blood
              donation. During this type of donation, you donate approximately half a liter of whole blood. The blood is
              then separated into its components: red blood cells, plasma, and sometimes platelets<br> .....</p>
            <a href="/users/servicesDetails" class="read-more"><span>Read More</span> <i
                class="bi bi-arrow-right"></i></a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-lg-4 col-md-6" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="300">
          <div class="service-box orange">
            <i class="ri-discuss-line icon"></i>
            <h3>apheresis</h3>
            <p>During apheresis, you'll be connected to a machine that collects and separates the different blood
              components. These blood components include red blood cells, plasma, and platelets. Then the machine works
              to return the remaining blood components to your body.

              In the case of a platelet donation (thrombopheresis), only the platelets are collected. Platelets are
              cells that help stop bleeding by forming clumps and blockages in blood vessels (thrombosis)</p>
            <a href="/users/servicesDetails" class="read-more"><span>Read More</span> <i
                class="bi bi-arrow-right"></i></a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-lg-4 col-md-6" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="400">
          <div class="service-box green">
            <i class="ri-discuss-line icon"></i>
            <h3>Why is this done?</h3>
            <p> You must agree to have a blood sample drawn from you for the purpose of giving it to another person who
              needs a blood transfusion.

              Millions of people need blood transfusions annually. Some may need blood while they are undergoing
              surgery. Others rely on it after an accident or a disease that requires access to some blood components.
              Donating blood allows all of this. There is no substitute for human blood; Therefore, all blood
              transfusions use blood from donors</p>
            <a href="/users/servicesDetails" class="read-more"><span>Read More</span> <i
                class="bi bi-arrow-right"></i></a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-lg-4 col-md-6" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="500">
          <div class="service-box red">
            <i class="ri-discuss-line icon"></i>
            <h3>Risks</h3>
            <p> Donating blood is a safe process. New, sterile, single-use kits are used for each donor. Therefore,
              there is no risk of blood transmission when donating blood.

              Most healthy adults can safely donate about a pint without any health risks. Within a few days of donating
              blood, your body will replace the lost fluids. After two weeks, your body will replace the lost red blood
              cells</p>
            <a href="/users/servicesDetails" class="read-more"><span>Read More</span> <i
                class="bi bi-arrow-right"></i></a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-lg-4 col-md-6" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="600">
          <div class="service-box purple">
            <i class="ri-discuss-line icon"></i>
            <h3>How do you prepare?</h3>
            <p>Eligibility requirements <br>
              To be eligible to donate whole blood, plasma or platelets, the following conditions must be met:
              <br>
              To be healthy.<br>
              Be at least 16 or 17 years old depending on the law in the state where you live. Some states allow legal
              minors to donate with parental consent. Although there is no maximum legal age, policies may vary between
              individual donation centers.<br>
              You weigh at least 110 lbs (approximately 50 kg).<br>
              Be able to pass physical and health history assessments.<br>
              Eligibility requirements vary slightly for different types of blood donation
            </p>
            <a href="/users/servicesDetails" class="read-more"><span>Read More</span> <i
                class="bi bi-arrow-right"></i></a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-lg-4 col-md-6" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="700">
